# API Authentication Standard

## Purpose

This rule defines authentication and authorization for FastAPI REST endpoints and their integration with the Next.js frontend.

Every protected resource must verify identity and permissions before executing use cases. Authentication failures must fail closed.

---

# Scope

Covers:

- Customer and admin authentication
- JWT and session cookie patterns
- FastAPI dependencies for auth
- Next.js server-side session usage
- Role-based access control (RBAC)
- Token refresh and logout

Does not cover payment provider auth (Stripe) — see payment skills.

---

# Authentication Models

| Consumer | Recommended mechanism |
|----------|----------------------|
| Next.js Server Components / Actions | HTTP-only session cookie |
| Next.js Client (browser) | Cookie via same-origin or BFF; no token in localStorage |
| Machine clients / future mobile | Bearer JWT (short-lived access + refresh) |
| Admin panel | Session cookie + elevated role + optional MFA |

Default e-commerce customer flow: session cookie issued by FastAPI, read by Next.js on the server.

---

# Session Cookie Flow

```
1. Customer POST /api/v1/auth/login (credentials)
2. FastAPI validates via AuthService
3. FastAPI sets Set-Cookie: session=...; HttpOnly; Secure; SameSite=Lax
4. Next.js Server Component forwards cookie on server-side fetch
5. FastAPI Depends(get_current_user) validates session on each request
```

Cookie attributes (production):

- `HttpOnly` — mandatory
- `Secure` — mandatory
- `SameSite=Lax` — default for e-commerce (adjust for cross-site if needed)
- `Path=/`
- Reasonable `Max-Age` or session cookie with server-side revocation

Never store JWT access tokens in `localStorage`.

---

# JWT Bearer Flow

For API clients and SPA-adjacent flows when cookies are impractical:

```
Authorization: Bearer <access_token>
```

Rules:

- Short access token TTL (15 minutes recommended)
- Refresh token rotation via `POST /api/v1/auth/refresh`
- Store refresh token HTTP-only or secure server-side
- Include `sub`, `exp`, `iat`, `jti` claims
- Sign with strong secret (RS256 preferred for multi-service)

Document bearer scheme in OpenAPI (`api/03-openapi`).

